SQAcore Automotive Data Product Platform is a sophisticated enterprise-grade data engineering platform I architected and developed over 2 years at Volkswagen Group, designed to support multiple automotive data products including basic-vehicle, scannable, parts-catalog, and other domain-specific solutions across the organization. The platform leverages a modern technology stack consisting of Apache Spark 3.4, Delta Lake, Trino, Docker, Kubernetes/OpenShift, and AWS S3/MinIO, orchestrated through Argo Workflows and managed via Bamboo CI/CD pipelines with JFrog Artifactory for artifact management and BitBucket for version control. At its core, the platform implements a sqa-core-common framework that provides reusable components including Spark client libraries, data source handlers, schema management utilities, and entity processing frameworks, enabling rapid development of new data products following consistent medallion architecture patterns (Entity → Integration Layer → Semantic Layer). The platform processes millions of automotive records daily from diverse legacy and modern source systems (including EBCDIC format handling for legacy automotive data), transforming raw manufacturing, vehicle lifecycle, warranty, delivery, and parts data into analytics-ready datasets. Key technical achievements include developing 20+ PySpark-based ETL jobs with 85% test coverage using PyTest and Behave frameworks, implementing real-time data validation and quality monitoring, optimizing query performance by 40% through advanced partitioning and caching strategies, and building containerized, auto-scaling deployments. The business impact has been substantial, reducing data product development time by 70%, improving processing efficiency from 8 hours to 2 hours, enhancing data accuracy by 25%, and standardizing data contracts across 8+ data products and 5+ business units, ultimately enabling faster business decision-making and improved operational efficiency across Volkswagen Group's automotive manufacturing and lifecycle management processes.
